Name: statusIconMenu

Type: property

Syntax: set the statusIconMenu to <menuString>

Summary:
Defines the context menu shown when the user right-clicks the system tray icon.

Introduced: 1.0.0

OS: windows

Platforms: desktop

Example:
-- Simple flat menu with tags
set the statusIconMenu to "Show App|show" & return \
    & "Hide App|hide" & return \
    & "-" & return \
    & "Quit|quit"

Example:
-- Menu with a submenu (tab-indented items become children of the item above)
set the statusIconMenu to "File" & return \
    & tab & "New|new" & return \
    & tab & "Open...|open" & return \
    & "-" & return \
    & "Quit|quit"

Example:
-- Disabled item using parenthesis prefix
set the statusIconMenu to "(No Connection|connect" & return \
    & "Preferences|prefs" & return \
    & "-" & return \
    & "Quit|quit"

Example:
-- Handle menu picks
on statusIconMenuPick pTag
    switch pTag
        case "show"
            show this stack
            break
        case "hide"
            hide this stack
            break
        case "prefs"
            go card "Preferences" of stack "Main"
            break
        case "quit"
            quit
            break
    end switch
end statusIconMenuPick

Example:
-- Handle a submenu pick (path is top-level to selected item, separated by |)
on statusIconMenuPick pTag
    -- Selecting "Open..." from the File submenu gives: "File|open"
    if pTag is "File|open" then
        answer file "Choose a file:"
    end if
end statusIconMenuPick

Example:
-- Remove the context menu
set the statusIconMenu to empty

Parameters:
menuString:
A return-separated list of menu item definitions. Each line defines one
item using the following format:

  [tabs][prefix]label[|tag]

- **tabs**: zero or more tab characters that determine submenu depth.
  Items indented one tab deeper than the item above them become children
  of that item (see Submenus below).

- **prefix**: an opening parenthesis `(` marks the item as disabled and
  greyed out. Use `((` as an escaped literal `(` in the label text.

- **label**: the text displayed in the menu. A label of exactly `-`
  produces a horizontal separator line.

- **|tag**: an optional tag passed to the `statusIconMenuPick` message
  when the item is chosen. If omitted, the label text is used as the tag.

Value:
The <statusIconMenu> returns the string most recently set.
The default value is empty (no context menu).

Description:
Use the <statusIconMenu> property to define the pop-up menu that appears
when the user right-clicks the system tray icon. The menu is rebuilt each
time any of <statusIcon>, <statusIconMenu>, or <statusIconTooltip> is set.

**Item format**

Each return-separated line represents one menu item. The label is the
visible text; the optional tag (after `|`) is what your script receives
in `statusIconMenuPick`. If no tag is given, the label is used as the tag.

**Separators**

A line whose label is exactly `-` (a single hyphen, after stripping any
leading tabs) draws a horizontal separator. Separators cannot be tagged.

**Disabled items**

Prefix a label with `(` to display it greyed-out and unclickable. To
include a literal `(` at the start of a label, use `((` instead.

**Submenus**

Items are nested into submenus using tab indentation. An item that is
indented one tab deeper than the previous top-level item becomes a child
of that item. Multiple levels of nesting are supported.

    "Parent" & return &
    tab & "Child 1|c1" & return &
    tab & "Child 2|c2" & return &
    "Next Top Level|ntl"

**Messages**

When the right-click menu is about to open, the `statusIconMenuOpening`
message is sent to the current card of the default stack. This lets you
update the menu contents before it is displayed.

When an item is chosen, `statusIconMenuPick` is sent with a single
parameter containing the item's tag. For items inside submenus the
parameter is a `|`-delimited path from the top-level parent down to the
selected item â€” for example, selecting "Child 2" from the example above
produces `"Parent|c2"`.

Setting <statusIconMenu> to empty removes the context menu; right-clicking
the tray icon will then have no visible effect (though `statusIconClick`
is still sent for the button-up event).

>*Note:* The <statusIconMenu> property is not persistent â€” it is not
> saved into the stack file.

>*Note:* The <statusIconMenu> property only has a visual effect on
> Windows. On macOS and Linux the property is accepted without error but
> has no effect.

References: statusIcon (property), statusIconTooltip (property),
statusIconMenuOpening (message), statusIconMenuPick (message),
statusIconClick (message)

Tags: windowing
